{"triple_norm": ["thegospelofjohn", "be write to", "thegreeks"], "true_link": {"object": "NULL", "subject": "/m/038vs"}, "src_sentences": ["The Gospel of John be write to the Greeks", "The security agent\u2019s eyes widened as he watched the monitor. He asked Tom what he had in the bag. Then the agent slowly pulled out of the bag this strange looking device, a six-by-three-inch black box covered with dials and switches. Other travelers, sensing trouble, vacated the area. It&apos;s a metronome, Tom replied weakly, as his son cringed in embarrassment. It&apos;s a talking metronome. Look, I&apos;ll show you.\u00a0 He took the box and flipped a switch, realizing that he had no idea how it worked. One . . . two . . . three . . . four, said the metronome in perfect time. Everyone breathed a sigh of relief.\u00a0 As they gathered their belongings, Tom&apos;s son whispered, Aren&apos;t you glad it didn&apos;t go \u201cfour . . . three . . . two . . . one . . . ?&quot; \u00a0 For the past few weeks we have been counting down the days until Christmas. Now we could count the hours until the dawning of a New Year. It is a good time to assess what we have accomplished in the past year and to establish some goals and determine what we want to accomplish in the new year. Sometimes we get discouraged about our ability to accomplish anything. It feels like the metronome of life is counting down and we are running out of time. We decide we are too old or too young, too poor or too powerless or we think we don\u2019t have the time or it isn\u2019t the right time to really do anything to make a difference in the world. The Gospel of Luke has some encouraging words for us. Each of the four Gospels is unique. Matthew was written primarily to people who were Jewish. A theme that runs through Matthew\u2019s gospel is, the promises of the Old Testament are fulfilled in Jesus. His account of Jesus\u2019 birth is laced with references to the prophesy of Isaiah and Micah. The Gospel of Mark was written to the people of Rome. Rome ruled the world at the time and they were into power. Mark is constantly referring to the power of Jesus and tells many miracle stories to illustrate that power. He doesn\u2019t even have an account of Christ\u2019s birth \u2013 probably because babies don\u2019t have much power. The Gospel of John was written to the Greeks. This gospel is much more intellectual and spiritual. While John doesn\u2019t have a birth narrative either, he does have an eloquent prologue in which he declares, The Word became flesh and dwelt among us.\u201d The gospel of Luke is written primarily to gentiles, those who were not Jewish. It is known as the Universal Gospel. More than the other three, Luke emphasizes that the good news of salvation in Christ is for everyone. Luke shows us that God loves the poor. Mary and Joseph were poor. The baby Jesus is born in a barn. Shepherds were poor \u2013 they were outcasts, and yet, in Luke\u2019s Gospel it was to shepherds that the angels came and announced the savior\u2019s birth. When Mary and Joseph came to the temple for Jesus\u2019 circumcision when he was 8 days old, they couldn\u2019t afford to sacrifice a lamb. They made the sacrifice allotted for poor people \u2013 two turtledoves. In the Sermon on the Mount, Matthew quotes Jesus as saying, Blessed are the poor in spirit. Luke quotes Jesus as saying, Blessed are you who are poor \u2013 not poor in spirit, just poor. When John the Baptist sends his disciples to ask Jesus if he is the Messiah Jesus answers by saying, Go and tell John what you have seen and heard: the blind receive their sight, the lame walk, the lepers* are cleansed, the deaf hear, the dead are raised, the poor have good news brought to them. Luke is the only one who tells the story of the poor man named Lazarus who lays at the rich man\u2019s gate hoping for a handout. It is Luke who tells the story of Zacchaeus who responds to Jesus\u2019 acceptance of him by giving half of his wealth to the poor. In the culture of the day being poor was seen as being out of favor with God. Rich people were seen as those most loved by God because God had given them all these blessings. Luke wants the world to know that God loves the poor and that Jesus came to bring the good news of salvation to them. Luke wants us to know that God values the poor and can use them to further his kingdom. You don\u2019t hear much about elderly people in the New Testament. The Old Testament had its fair share of ancient patriarchs and matriarchs. Methuselah lived more than 900 years. Abraham was over 100 and wrinkled old Sarah was over 90 when Isaac was born. King David lived to a ripe old age. There are others as well. But about the only older people in the New Testament we get to know reasonably well are introduced in the first two chapters of Luke: Zechariah and Elizabeth; Simeon and Anna. Despite the fact that the metronome of time is counting down for them, these ancient and wizened people of faith bear witness to who Jesus is and what he will do. The Holy Spirit told Simeon that he will not die before he sees the promised Messiah. When he sees Joseph and Mary bringing the baby Jesus to the temple he asked to hold him. Then he praised God saying, It is OK if I die now because I have seen your salvation which you have prepared in the presence of all peoples, a light for the revelation to the Gentiles and for glory to your people Israel. Simeon also predicts great pain for Mary knowing that her son will suffer and die for the sake of the world. And 84 year old Anna, who spends day and night in the temple praying, begins to tell everyone about this child who will redeem the world. Luke wants us to know that God can use senior citizens too. That is a message our culture needs to hear. In China, Japan and in many African nations older people are revered and respected. In the U. S. we tend to discount older people and see them as having outlived their usefulness. But like Simeon and Anna, many Christians who are older have a great witness to share and can tell how God has been at work in their lives. An important aspect of the witness of both Simeon and Anna is that this child is sent to be the savior of all people. He is not just the savior of the Jews, but he is God\u2019s salvation prepared in the presence of all people, a light for revelation to the Gentiles. Luke wants us to know that Jesus came to bring salvation to everyone \u2013 Jew and Gentile. In the book of Acts, Luke\u2019s sequel to his Gospel, Peter has a vision that reveals to him that he is to share the good news with Cornelius and other gentiles. And the majority of the book of Acts is an account of Paul\u2019s missionary journeys where he establishes new churches with mostly gentile members. The story of Anna and her witness to Jesus is just one way that Luke emphasizes the worth of women. In Jesus day women were seen as property. They didn\u2019t have many rights. They were not even allowed to testify in court because they were not seen as reliable witnesses. Mary, the mother of Jesus, plays a very important role in Luke\u2019s Gospel as do many other women. Luke is the only Gospel that tells the story of Jesus raising the son of the widow of Nain and the story of the sinful woman who washes Jesus\u2019 feet with her tears, wipes them with her hair and anoints them with expensive perfume. His is the only account of Jesus healing the woman who had suffered for 18 years with an illness that kept her back bent over. The parable of the Lost Coin is also unique to Luke as he uses a woman as an image of God searching for lost sinners. He is the only one who tells the parable of the Widow and the Judge, teaching us to be persistent in prayer. And in Luke, as in the other Gospels, women are the first witnesses to the resurrection. A recurring message in Luke is that God values women and that women can engage in meaningful ministry. Like women, children were not seen to have much worth in Jesus\u2019 day. It was important to have children, but until they matured into adulthood they weren\u2019t seen as all that valuable. Luke frequently emphasizes the importance of children. His gospel has the only story of the birth of John the Baptist. He gives the most extensive account of the birth of Jesus. He is the only one to tell the story of Jesus as a boy staying behind to teach the teachers in the temple. And like Matthew and Mark, Luke tells the story of Jesus blessing the children and saying, Truly I tell you, whoever does not receive the kingdom of God as a little child will never enter it. Luke wants us to know that God loves all of us and can use all of us to accomplish his will in the world. He can use us whether we are rich or poor; a child or a senior citizen; a male or a female. He can use people of all races and colors. He can use you and he can use me. There are churches that list the name of their pastors in the bulletin and then they say: Ministers \u2013 all. We are all ministers whether we are ordained or not. In reality the real work of the church is done by the people, not just the pastors. As hard as we might work Pastors Shelley, Deb, Ed and I could never do all the things that are accomplished by this congregation. As pastors our role is not to do all the ministry, but rather to inspire, empower and enable others to use their varied gifts in ministry. And you do a wonderful job of that here at Christ the King. It is amazing how much ministry is accomplished here and how much of it is done by people working out of the spotlight, behind the scenes. I may preside at communion, but I would be in big trouble if it weren\u2019t for people who fill the wine cups and bread trays and prepared the table. We have greeters and ushers and worship coordinators; welcome center hosts, sound and light technicians, videographers and projectionists; lectors, communion servers and musicians \u2013 both instrumentalists and vocalists. We have people who stuff the bulletins and make sure hymnals and Bibles are arranged in the pews. There are a whole host of people who do different jobs to make sure our worship services go smoothly. And that is just one area of our ministry. Tons of volunteers are needed and utilized in all our other ministry areas. Like quarterbacks in football, pastors probably get both too much credit when things go well and too much blame when things go poorly. In football and in church it is really a team effort. Viking running back Adrian Peterson is on a record setting pace for yardage gained. When he is interviewed he always makes sure to give credit to his offensive line. He reminds the media that football is a team game and that no running back can gain many yards unless their linemen open up a hole for them. Here at Christ the King many people are working on annual reports, summarizing what has been accomplished in their ministry area in the past year. For over a year, the congregation and council have been working on a Strategic Plan. We have developed a vision statement that says what we hope Christ the King to be in the future. It says: Christ the King Lutheran Church is a growing community where people of all ages are inspired and transformed to live for Christ. Creating faith for life through EXCELLENCE in: Worship Music Education Service and Outreach We have a retreat scheduled on Saturday, January 17 to continue work on the strategic plan. I hope you will attend that important retreat because we want as many people to share their input on the plan as possible. But even more, I hope you will use these days as the metronome of time ticks down the last hours of this year and ushers in a new year to assess how you might share your gifts and talents in ministry. For Luke assures us that God loves and can use all of us: rich and poor; young and old; male and female. God is calling us into ministry. How will we answer? Amen."], "triple": ["The Gospel of John", "be write to", "the Greeks"], "kbp_info": [], "entity_linking": {"object": null, "subject": null}, "_id": 3993}
